Trader Behavior Insights Based on Bitcoin Market Sentiment


Objective
To analyze the relationship between trader performance and Bitcoin market sentiment (Fear, Greed, Neutral, etc.), and to uncover patterns that can help improve trading strategies.


Datasets Used
Historical Trader Data
Source: Provided dataset
Key Columns: Account, Coin, Execution Price, Size, Side, Timestamp, Closed PnL, etc.

Bitcoin Market Sentiment Data
Source: Provided dataset
Key Columns: Date, Classification (Fear/Greed/Neutral)


Methodology
Cleaned and converted date-time formats.

Merged trader data with sentiment data on the trade date.

Explored trader profitability and trade volumes across different sentiment phases.

Visualized patterns using Python, Pandas, Matplotlib, and Seaborn.


Key Findings
Trader activity was highest during "Greed" and "Extreme Greed" phases.

Average profits per trade were different across sentiments:

Profits tend to be higher in "Extreme Greed" phases.

Trader activity is lower but more cautious in "Extreme Fear" phases.

Sentiment has a noticeable impact on both trade volume and profitability.


